{"cards":[{"lines":[{"type":"title","text":"Vector magnitude from components"},{"type":"headline","text":"Use Pythagorean theorem"},{"type":"headline","text":"  <math>    <mrow>      <msup>        <mi>A<\/mi>        <mn>2<\/mn>      <\/msup>      <mo>=<\/mo>      <msub>        <mi>A<\/mi>        <mi>x<\/mi>      <\/msub>      <msup>        <mtext>\u00a0<\/mtext>        <mn>2<\/mn>      <\/msup>      <mo>+<\/mo>      <msub>        <mi>A<\/mi>        <mi>y<\/mi>      <\/msub>      <msup>        <mtext>\u00a0<\/mtext>        <mn>2<\/mn>      <\/msup>    <\/mrow>  <\/math>"},{"type":"headline","text":"  <math>    <mrow>      <mi>A<\/mi>      <mo>=<\/mo>      <msqrt>        <mrow>          <msub>            <mi>A<\/mi>            <mi>x<\/mi>          <\/msub>          <msup>            <mtext>\u00a0<\/mtext>            <mn>2<\/mn>          <\/msup>          <mo>+<\/mo>          <msub>            <mi>A<\/mi>            <mi>y<\/mi>          <\/msub>          <msup>            <mtext>\u00a0<\/mtext>            <mn>2<\/mn>          <\/msup>        <\/mrow>      <\/msqrt>    <\/mrow>  <\/math>"}]}],"definitions":[],"secText":["If we are given the <a class='pjumpToVideo' href='javascript:void(0)' data-video='true' data-vref='wb_vector_velocity_fundamentals1'>components<\/a> of a vector, we can calculate its magnitude.  The two components are legs of a right triangle, because the <i>x<\/i><i>-<\/i> and <i>y<\/i>-axes are perpendicular (at right angles) to each other.  ","The Pythagorean theorem states that the sum of the squares of the legs equals the square of the hypotenuse.  We take the square root of the sum of the squared legs to solve for the hypotenuse. ","The two components can be added like vectors, as shown in the diagram, to determine the overall direction of the vector.  "],"objNames":["wb_vector_magnitude"]}